text:
9:44 Engineer (ing major) here: you can throw a rock in space, but when you throw it you gain some velocity backwards while the rock moves forwards. Because the rock's mass is lower than your own, the rock would gain more forward velocity while you gain just a tiny amount of backward velocity. That is because of a law called "conservation of momentum". In technical terms a closed system's momentum is conserved no matter what kind of mechanical reaction occurs, also momentum is velocity times mass of an object. (This is how rockets work actually, think of the super-heated fuel molecules as small rocks and the rocket throws it out the back to gain velocity.) This means that the momentum of you with a stone in your hand equals to the you + the stone after you throw it. For example lets say you have 0 momentum before you throw the rock because in your reference frame you are standing still:
0 momentum = 0 velocity * (mass of you + mass of stone)
# you throw the stone and now it has some velocity
(velocity of stone * mass of stone) + (- velocity of you * mass of you ) = 0 #the sum of momentum doesn't change, the velocity of you is negative because you are moving backwards now.
therefore: velocity of stone * mass of stone = velocity of you * mass of you
therefore: velocity of stone / velocity of you = mass of you / mass of stone 
so if your mass is greater than the stone, the speed of stone must be bigger than yours
( speed and velocity are different by the way, velocity is a vector and has direction, speed is a scalar quantity and has no direction velocity = speed * unitary direction vector therefore velocity can be negative in a reference frame while the speed is always a non negative real number  (between 0 and positive infinity))

Thus if you and the other guy are not moving relative to each other (not gaining distance or losing distance) you can hurt somebody if you can throw the rock well enough. But with the positive outwards pressure of EVA suits I doubt you can kill anybody (also I think EVA suits are protected against small space debris ? Somebody do correct me on that)
